properties.context: The finder, who retained the coin, would not give the exact location, but said that the coin was found about two feet below the surface on a building site where no building work had previously taken place. The coin, which was in fair condition, had on the obverse the head of Zeus, and on the reverse, an eagle standing upon a thunderbolt. the coin would appear to be a genuine archaeological find rather than a chance recent loss, and takes its place with the two Greek silver coins found at Holne (SX 76 NW 3,5) which demonstrated South Wstern connections with the Mediterranean in the Early Iron Age. properties.description: A house standing at the road junction where, in 1988, Mr E. G. Jeal dug up a billon tetradrachm of Alexandria, with a good patina, which he presented to the Royal Institution of Cornwall.

Killibury, or Kelly Rounds, is an Iron Age camp. No coins have been found there, but on 17 August 1921, Mr A. L. Hoskin and two other youths, found coins in a trench about two feet deep dug by workmen at the back of a cattle-shed at Sandylands farm. The coins include a bronze coin of Carthage, Zeugitana, north Africa, Roman imperial coins and one billon tetradrachm of Alexandria, all of which were presented to the Royal Institution of Cornwall in 1979. The strange association must comprise a modern loss.

properties.knownas: Roman coins have been found in the parish at different dates, and a coin hoard deposited ca.390 was found in 1923. More information : Roman coins from Honiton: Diocletan, AD 284-305, minted at Alexandria. Found 1907.Maximim II, AD 308-14. Found 1947. Coins in Exeter Museum (Rougemont House). A bronze coin of Maxim (AD 305-313) found in Honiton parish was acquired by Exeter Museum in 1947. No details of the site are known. A hoard of sixteen late Roman coins, from Constantius II to Arcadius, was found at Honiton, Devon, about 1923. it is believed to have been deposited about 390 AD. See also: Lecture by Amelia Dowler (17:35). Coin in Collection of Royal Albert Memorial Museum, Exeter

Although this coin dates from the time the Second Legion Augusta were based in Exeter, this type of coin was not commonly circulated in Britain. They are most commonly found in the eastern Mediterranean, and it is possible this coin was lost by a collector in the recent past.

properties.description: A bronze coin of Probus(A.D. 276 - 282) minted at Alexandria found [c.1950?] by Mr. Spurway at Corner Cottage, Yarcombe, whilst digging in his garden. "Corner Cottage" appears to be the most northerly of the two of cottages opposite Yarcombe Inn, (b) at [ST 24470823] Corner Cottage Grade 3. Mrs. Spurway, now living at 7, The Council Houses, Monkton [between Yarcombe & Honiton] indicated on the O.S. 25" the point at which the coin was found. (ST 2446 0825). The coin is in her husband's possession.
Copper alloy coin, almost certainly ancient 19mm; 8.64g; 4mm thick Obverse: illegible; possibly a bust right Reverse: illegible details, possibly an X Condition: almost totally effaced: Very Poor
properties.notes_1: The fabric of this coin suggests that it could be a Greek bronze of the 3rd to 2nd centuries BC, or it could be a Roman Tetradrachm from a 3rd century issue at Alexandria. It is impossible to be sure, however, if it is either.
